<h2>Autumn Storms</h2>
<br><br>
The first autumn storm of the season hit Europe on 5 and 6 October 2017. The storm caused considerable damage in a band from Holland, over northern Germany and into Poland. This windstorm, named Xavier by the German Weather Service (DWD), caused severe damage and left a number of people dead.
<br><br>
As the storm passed through the region, it produced wind gusts up to 35-40 m/s (130 km/h), downing trees, damaging buildings and causing severe traffic chaos.
<br><br>
Furthermore, many problems resulted from the high wind and storm surges occurred in Northern Germany and along the coasts of the Baltic Sea. In the image you can see the location of the vigorous developing low pressure area (October 5th 06Z) together with the track in the whole 48 hour period (denoted by the stars).
<br><br>
<a href="../images/oct2017/Plaatje_Storm_October_2017.png"><img alt="" src="../images/oct2017/Plaatje_Storm_October_2017.png" width="350px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: The location to the vigorous developing low pressure area on October 5th 06Z. The stars indicate the track of this depression in the 48 hour period.</em>
<br><br>
During the 5th of October wind gusts of 176 km/h occurred at station Brocken (Germany, 1134 m), 202 km/h at station Sniezka (Poland, 1603 m) and 122 km/h gusts were reported at Berlin airport (Germany); a great deal of damage resulted from fallen trees. At least seven people died and the public transport in northern Germany was severely disrupted (cancelled flights and cancelled long-distance trains to and from Berlin partly for several days).
<br><br>
Half-way through the month of October (on the 15, 16 and 17th), Storm Ophelia hit Ireland, Scotland and Norway. The storm, which reached wind speeds of 150 km/h, caused at least three deaths and significant material damage. About 360,000 Irish residents suffered from lost power supplies. The situation was exceptional: such a storm depression, formed out of a tropical hurricane of category 3, has never been so close to Europe. This year's hurricane season was very intense, with the simultaneous presence of three hurricanes: Irma, Jose and Katia.
<br><br>
Ophelia started as a tropical storm at about 1500 km southwest of the Azores and moved in a Northeast direction, and not to the West of the islands which is usual (Satellite film from Deutscher Wetterdienst: <a href="https://youtu.be/9fsPVgsJbc0" target="_blank">https://youtu.be/9fsPVgsJbc0</a>). On Saturday 14 October, Ophelia was still a hurricane of category 3. That was because of the exceptional sea surface temperatures, which were approximately two degrees higher than usual.
<br><br>
On the way to Ireland, Ophelia reduced to a tropical storm and gradually acquired the characteristics of a mid-latitude autumn storm, driven by the usual storm-jet stream dynamics at mid latitudes. The exceptional nature of Ophelia was that during this extra tropical transition the core of the storm still contained warm moist air, providing an additional driving force that is typical for tropical hurricanes.
<br><br>
Also a "sting jet" occurred: strong winds in the middle atmosphere (at an altitude of 3 to 4 km) that reached the ground for a short time. This would explain the very high wind speeds that were measured. These winds caused major damage, similar to <a href="https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/learning/learn-about-the-weather/weather-phenomena/case-studies/great-storm" target="_blank">the great Storm of 16 October 1987</a>, exactly thirty years ago.
<br><br>
<h2>Saharan dust and smoke over Western Europe</h2>
<br><br>
<a href="../images/oct2017/Fires.png"><img alt="" src="../images/oct2017/Fires.png" width="300px"></a>
<a href="../images/oct2017/AOD.png"><img alt="" src="../images/oct2017/AOD.png" width="300px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2: CAMS GFAS Observed Fire Radiative Power Areal Density on 16 October 2017 (Left); CAMS AerosolOptical Depth @550nm on 16 October 2017 (Right)</em>
<br><br>
The exceptionally high surface temperatures and low precipitation amounts in Southwest Europe lead to devastating forest fires in Northern Portugal and Spain (Figure 2, left). Smoke from these fires as well as desert dust and sea salt, were detected by the <a href="https://atmosphere.copernicus.eu" target="_blank">Copernicus Atmospheric Monitoring Service</a> (Figure 2, right), clearly indicating transport of these aerosols from to the North due too the strong southerly winds related to ex-hurricane Ophelia.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/oct2017/Lidar.png"><img alt="" src="../images/oct2017/Lidar.png" width="300px"></a>
<a href="../images/oct2017/BSRNv3.png"><img alt="" src="../images/oct2017/BSRNv3.png" width="300px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 3: LIDAR ceilometer measurements in De Bilt, The Netherlands on 16, 17, and 18 October (Left); BSRN Direct Normal Radiation measured in Cabauw, The Netherlands, on the 17th and on the 15th of October (as a reference for a clear day with normal aerosol concentrations) (Right)</em>
<br><br>
On October 17, LIDAR ceilometer measurements in De Bilt (Figure 3, left) indicated a significant amount of aerosol at an altitude between 0 and 3 km. Below 6 km no clouds were observed on this day. Figure 3 (right) shows the strong impact of the aerosol layer on direct surface radiation observed at the nearby BSRN station in Cabauw, the Netherlands.
<br><br>
Weather balloon measurements showed that the air temperature between 1 and 3 kilometers altitude was several degrees higher, while temperatures close to the ground were several degrees lower than predicted by regional models, that currently do not incorporate these aerosol dynamics.
<br><br>
<h2>The weather in October 2017</h2>
<h3>Temperature deviations and extremes</h3>
<br><br>
The distribution in October 2017 of the daily average temperatures over Europe based on surface observations, shows average or below average values in the East (Russia, Finland, Baltic states, Belarus) and much higher than normal values in Western and Central Europe (Figures 3 and 4). Spain, Portugal and Southern France stand out with exceptionally high values for the daily average temperature. This difference between East and West is even more prominent in the daily maximum temperatures (the rightmost maps in Figures 3 and 4). Interestingly, the East-West gradient is much less pronounced in the daily minimum temperature (leftmost maps in Figures 3 and 4). A likely cause for these observations are in the monthly averaged cloud cover and incoming solar radiation observed by Meteosat (Figures 13 and 14). They show a similar East - West gradient with high cloud cover / low incoming solar radiation in the East, and the opposite in Southwest Europe.
